@article{2004ApJ...615L..65S,
	Abstract = {{We explore the possibility for the formation of Population III binaries.
The collapse of a rotating cylinder is simulated with a
three-dimensional, high-resolution nested grid, assuming the thermal
history of primordial gas. The simulations are done with dimensionless
units, and the results are applicable to low-mass as well as massive
systems by scaling with the initial density. We find that if the initial
angular momentum is as small as {$\beta$}\~{}0.1, where {$\beta$} is the ratio of
centrifugal force to pressure force and is of the order of 10\%, then the
runaway collapse of the cloud stops to form a rotationally supported
disk. After the accretion of the envelope, the disk undergoes a ring
instability, eventually fragmenting into a binary. If the initial
angular momentum is relatively large, a bar-type instability arises,
resulting in the collapse into a single star through rapid angular
momentum transfer. The present results show that a significant fraction
of Population III stars are expected to form in binary systems, even if
they are quite massive or less massive. The cosmological implications of
Population III binaries are briefly discussed.
}},
